{"title":"Train Once, Deploy Anywhere: Matryoshka Representation Learning for Multimodal Recommendation","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Sequential recommenders often need different embedding/model sizes to balance accuracy and efficiency across deployment settings, but training and tuning separate models for each size is costly and inflexible.","method":"fMRLRec extends Matryoshka Representation Learning to sequential recommendation by nesting multiple granularities M={2,4,8,...,D} inside a single model and optimizing them jointly. It introduces an fMRLRec operator that applies structured masking to weight matrices so the first M[j] input channels only interact with corresponding weight blocks, enabling all sub-dimensions to be trained in one forward/backward pass and later extracted by slicing weights for deployment. The training objective adds explicit multi-dimension loss terms to directly supervise each sub-model. A Linear Recurrent Unit (LRU) state-space backbone provides parallel training and efficient inference, yielding a train-once, deploy-anywhere framework. (Supported by: lines 56–79, 80–94, 150–156, 164–169, 118–131, 133–147)."},{"problem":"Integrating textual and visual item attributes into sequential recommenders without heavy fusion modules while ensuring the features align in a shared space.","method":"fMRLRec encodes item text (title, price, brand, categories) and images using pretrained encoders, concatenates the embeddings, and applies a single linear projection to align them into the model’s hidden dimension D. This lightweight fusion plugs directly into the LRU-based sequence module. Ablations show both modalities contribute to performance, with language features having the larger impact. (Supported by: lines 100–117, 261–269, 243–256)."},{"problem":"Training multi-granularity recommendation models independently imposes substantial memory and compute overhead for parameters and activations.","method":"By embedding smaller weights and activations into larger ones via the fMRLRec linear transformation and computing all slices with a single masked matrix multiplication, fMRLRec avoids training separate models. Theoretical analysis shows about 33% savings in parameters and activations compared to independently training each size, and empirical results confirm convergence toward this savings across target sizes. (Supported by: lines 26–31, 171–187, 241–242)."}]}
